"Pech D., Aguirre-Macedo M.L., Lewis J.W., Vidal-Martínez V.M.","Rainfall induces time-lagged changes in the proportion of tropical aquatic hosts infected with metazoan parasites",2010,"International Journal for Parasitology","40","8",,"937","944",,,10.1016/j.ijpara.2010.01.009,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77953019787&partnerID=40&md5=258035135c0f4f3d2c27e7e0083685a8","Laboratorio de Parasitología, Departamento de Recursos del Mar, Cinvestav-IPN Unidad Mérida, Carretera antigua a Progreso km 6, Apdo. Postal 73 - Cordemex, 97310 Mérida, Yucatán, Mexico; Centro EPOMEX, Universidad Autónoma de Campeche, Av. Agustin Melgar S/N Col. Buenavista, Campeche 24039, Mexico; Department of Ecology, Evolution and Marine Biology and Marine Science Institute, University of California, Santa Barbara, CA 93106, United States; School of Biological Sciences, Royal Holloway University of London, Egham, Surrey TW20 0EX, United Kingdom","Pech, D., Laboratorio de Parasitología, Departamento de Recursos del Mar, Cinvestav-IPN Unidad Mérida, Carretera antigua a Progreso km 6, Apdo. Postal 73 - Cordemex, 97310 Mérida, Yucatán, Mexico, Centro EPOMEX, Universidad Autónoma de Campeche, Av. Agustin Melgar S/N Col. Buenavista, Campeche 24039, Mexico; Aguirre-Macedo, M.L., Laboratorio de Parasitología, Departamento de Recursos del Mar, Cinvestav-IPN Unidad Mérida, Carretera antigua a Progreso km 6, Apdo. Postal 73 - Cordemex, 97310 Mérida, Yucatán, Mexico, Department of Ecology, Evolution and Marine Biology and Marine Science Institute, University of California, Santa Barbara, CA 93106, United States; Lewis, J.W., School of Biological Sciences, Royal Holloway University of London, Egham, Surrey TW20 0EX, United Kingdom; Vidal-Martínez, V.M., Laboratorio de Parasitología, Departamento de Recursos del Mar, Cinvestav-IPN Unidad Mérida, Carretera antigua a Progreso km 6, Apdo. Postal 73 - Cordemex, 97310 Mérida, Yucatán, Mexico, Department of Ecology, Evolution and Marine Biology and Marine Science Institute, University of California, Santa Barbara, CA 93106, United States","Rainfall serves as a powerful driving force, shifting temporal abundance and prevalence patterns in parasites and free-living aquatic organisms in tropical environments. However, there is a lack of sound evidence showing the temporal scales at which rainfall influences infection parameters of parasites in the tropics either directly by affecting the parasite life cycle or indirectly by modifying host population abundance. In the present study, we demonstrate that changes in rainfall patterns lead to changes in the proportion of infected hosts with several parasite species, causing immediate or lagged favourable conditions for an increase in levels of infection. However, the temporal scale of the influence of rainfall varied depending on the ecological characteristics of aquatic ecosystems. Despite the environmental heterogeneity and stochastic events (storms and hurricanes) which affect the study sites, the proportion of infected hosts shows frequency cycles on a yearly scale, suggesting that environmental changes are within the range of variability that naturally occur at the study sites. We propose that the incorporation of stochastic events into long-term predictive models is crucial for understanding the potential effects of global climate change on infection parameters of tropical parasites. © 2010 Australian Society for Parasitology Inc.","Metazoan parasites; Seasonality; Stochastic events; Temporal scales; Tropical environments","rain; abundance; climate change; environmental change; global climate; metazoan; parasite; rainfall; seasonality; tropical environment; aquatic species; article; Cerithidea pliculosa; Cichlasoma urophthalma; climate change; controlled study; ecosystem; environmental change; genetic heterogeneity; helminth; host parasite interaction; hurricane; metazoon; nonhuman; prediction; proportion infected host; Pyrgophorus coronatus; seasonal varia